{"id":"1704.08844","submitter":"Jan Nagel","authors":"Noam Berger, Nina Gantert, Jan Nagel","title":"The speed of biased random walk among random conductances","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider biased random walk among iid, uniformly elliptic conductances on\n$\\mathbb{Z}^d$, and investigate the monotonicity of the velocity as a function\nof the bias. It is not hard to see that if the bias is large enough, the\nvelocity is increasing as a function of the bias. Our main result is that if\nthe disorder is small, i.e. all the conductances are close enough to each\nother, the velocity is always strictly increasing as a function of the bias,\nsee Theorem 1. A crucial ingredient of the proof is a formula for the\nderivative of the velocity, which can be written as a covariance, see Theorem\n3: it follows along the lines of the proof of the Einstein relation in [GGN].\nOn the other hand, we give a counterexample showing that for iid, uniformly\nelliptic conductances, the velocity is not always increasing as a function of\nthe bias. More precisely, if $d=2$ and if the conductances take the values $1$\n(with probability $p$) and $\\kappa$ (with probability $1-p$) and $p$ is close\nenough to $1$ and $\\kappa$ small enough, the velocity is not increasing as a\nfunction of the bias, see Theorem 2.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 28 Apr 2017 08:40:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-05-01"}
